<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the `sys_hub_flow` row that
    declares the `x_casemgmt_validate_resolved_transition` Flow Designer
    SUBFLOW (type=subflow) inside the scoped application `x_casemgmt`
    (Case Management).

    PURPOSE (AAP Section 0.5.5 verbatim transition row):
        From          To         Required condition / blocking-error behavior
        In Progress   Resolved   All linked x_casemgmt_case_task records have
                                 status = Closed.
                                 Failure: Surface form-level error
                                 "All tasks must be closed before resolving
                                  this case." (AAP Section 0.7.4 verbatim)

    This subflow is the MOST CRITICAL of the FIVE shared transition-
    validation subflows under `servicenow-case-management-poc/flows/
    sub_flows/` because it enforces the AAP Section 0.7.4 verbatim error
    message that is explicitly tested in Validation Gate 2
    ("task-closure check blocks Resolved transition" - AAP Section 0.7.3).
    It is called by both parent state-machine flows whenever a case's
    `status` field changes to `Resolved`:

      - ../general_inquiry_state_machine.xml
            (when a General Inquiry case enters the Resolved status)
      - ../complaint_state_machine.xml
            (when a Complaint case enters the Resolved status)

    UNLIKE the simpler validate_pending_transition.xml peer subflow
    (which has no validation gate), this subflow has:

      - A REQUIRED-CONDITION GATE: All child x_casemgmt_case_task rows
        must have status = 'Closed' before the case can transition to
        Resolved. The gate is enforced by calling
        x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator.canTransitionToResolved(case_record)
        which delegates to its getOpenTaskCountForCase(caseSysId) helper.
        That helper uses GlideAggregate('x_casemgmt_case_task') with
        addQuery('case', caseSysId) and addQuery('status', '!=', 'Closed')
        to count open tasks. If the count is greater than zero, the
        validator returns { ok: false, error: '...verbatim message...' }.

      - A THROW ERROR STEP: When the validator returns ok=false, the
        subflow's If/Then step branches to a Throw Error action that
        surfaces the verbatim AAP Section 0.7.4 error message
        "All tasks must be closed before resolving this case." on the
        form. Per ServiceNow Flow Designer semantics, Throw Error in a
        synchronously-invoked subflow propagates upward to the parent
        flow's triggering update operation, causing setAbortAction(true)
        on the underlying GlideRecord update and producing
        gs.addErrorMessage(<verbatim message>) on the form.

      - NO ROLE CHECK. Unlike validate_closed_transition.xml (which
        verifies the caller has the x_casemgmt_case_manager role), this
        subflow imposes no role gate. Per AAP Section 0.5.5 the
        In Progress -> Resolved transition's only required condition
        is the all-tasks-closed gate; the caller's role is governed
        entirely by the table-level ACLs in
        ../../acl/x_casemgmt_case_*.xml (case_agent and case_manager
        both have write access to assigned cases per AAP Section 0.5.6).

      - NO SIDE EFFECT ON SUCCESS. Unlike validate_pending_transition
        (which sets pending_reason) and validate_closed_transition
        (which sets closed_date), the Resolved transition has no field
        to auto-set. The subflow validates and returns. The case row's
        status field is set by the parent flow's normal status-update
        path (the form save that triggered the parent flow), so this
        subflow performs no GlideRecord update of its own.

    SEMANTIC SOURCE-SIDE REFERENCE (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported):

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/
        java/com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/service/
        CaseFileTasksService.java (interface) and
        CaseFileTasksServiceImpl.java (implementation)
            ArkCase aggregated tasks for a case via Solr search through
            the ChildDocumentsSearchService.searchForChildrenAndGrand
            childrenTasks call. The Java interface declared
            getCaseFileTasks(Long caseId, String parentType, Long
            parentId, List childTypes, String sort, Integer startRow,
            Integer maxRows, Authentication authentication) which
            returned a Solr response string. The ServiceNow target
            replaces this entirely with the Script Include's
            getOpenTaskCountForCase(caseSysId) which uses
            GlideAggregate for an efficient SQL COUNT(*) query - no
            Solr engine needed, no separate index to maintain. Solr
            is out of POC scope per AAP Section 0.3.2.

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/
        java/com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/service/
        ChangeCaseFileStateService.java
            * line 79-114 changeCaseState(auth, caseId, newState,
              ipAddress) - the central case state-machine service in
              ArkCase. The single method covered every transition by
              string-matching the newState parameter. The ServiceNow
              target splits this into FIVE per-transition subflows;
              this subflow is the In Progress -> Resolved slice. The
              ArkCase method does NOT enforce the all-tasks-closed
              gate (that gate did not exist in ArkCase as a hard rule
              because Solr-backed task aggregation was used only for
              UI display, not enforcement). The ServiceNow target
              ADDS the gate per AAP Section 0.5.5 explicit requirement.

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-task-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/task/model/AcmTask.java
            The task entity. Its status field has multiple states
            in ArkCase; the AAP simplifies to three values for the
            POC (Open, In Progress, Closed). The "all tasks closed"
            check in this subflow counts tasks where status is NOT
            exactly the literal string 'Closed'. Tasks with status
            'Open' or 'In Progress' (the only other legal Choice
            values per AAP Section 0.5.7 and
            ../../choices/sys_choice_case_task_status.xml) are
            counted as open and block the Resolved transition.

    SUBFLOW INPUTS (Flow Designer declarative parameters):

      1. case_record  (Reference to x_casemgmt_case, MANDATORY)
            Passed in by the parent flow as $trigger.current. This is
            the case row whose status is transitioning to Resolved.
            The parent flow's OnUpdate trigger fires when status
            changes to 'Resolved', and the trigger's $trigger.current
            is the just-updated case GlideRecord. The Script Include's
            canTransitionToResolved method uses
            caseGr.getUniqueValue() to obtain the case's sys_id, then
            passes that sys_id to the GlideAggregate query against
            x_casemgmt_case_task. The sys_id is a RUNTIME value
            (computed by the platform when the case row was inserted),
            NOT a hardcoded literal - this is the sole reason
            "no hardcoded sys_ids" rule does not preclude the use of
            sys_id values inside this subflow's logic.

    SUBFLOW STEPS (ordered):

      Step 1: Validate Resolved Transition (all tasks closed check)
            A Script Step that:
                a) Instantiates the Script Include:
                       var validator = new x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator();
                b) Invokes the per-transition guard with the supplied
                   case_record GlideRecord:
                       var result = validator.canTransitionToResolved(
                           fd_data.subflow_inputs.case_record);
                c) Exposes two outputs to the subflow execution context:
                       outputs.ok            = result.ok            (Boolean)
                       outputs.error_message = result.error || ''   (String)
            The Script Include's canTransitionToResolved returns:
                { ok: true }  - when zero open child tasks remain
                { ok: false, error: 'All tasks must be closed before
                                    resolving this case.' }
                              - when at least one child task has
                                status != 'Closed' (the verbatim AAP
                                Section 0.7.4 message)
                { ok: false, error: 'Case record is missing.' }
                              - when caseGr is null/undefined (defensive
                                guard inside the Script Include)
            The verbatim AAP message comes from the Script Include
            unmodified; this subflow does not compose its own message.

      Step 2: If validator returned not-ok
            An If/Then condition that branches when:
                fd_data._step_outputs.ok == false
            The branch contains a single Throw Error action.

      Step 2a: Throw Error (surfaces verbatim message on form)
            The Throw Error action's message is bound to the Script
            Step's error_message output. At runtime, when the
            condition is true and the action fires, the platform:
                a) Calls gs.addErrorMessage(error_message) on the
                   current update transaction's session.
                b) Aborts the parent flow's triggering update
                   (the implicit setAbortAction(true) on Throw Error).
                c) Returns control to the form, which displays the
                   error message at the top of the form.
            The error message text is EXACTLY:
                "All tasks must be closed before resolving this case."
            (the verbatim AAP Section 0.7.4 string, character-for-
            character including the trailing period and lowercase
            'case'). The message is propagated through the Script
            Include's return value; both the snapshot and the
            description above also embed the literal verbatim
            message for documentation/audit purposes.

      Step 3: End (implicit success path)
            When the If condition evaluates to false (validator
            returned ok=true), no Throw Error fires and the subflow
            returns successfully to the parent flow. No outputs are
            exposed to the parent because the parent flow does not
            need a return value - the absence of a thrown error is
            the success signal.

    OUTPUTS:
        None at the subflow level. The internal Script Step exposes
        ok and error_message outputs but those are scoped to the
        subflow and consumed only by the subsequent If/Throw Error
        step. The subflow itself returns no value to the parent.

    SCOPED-NAMESPACE CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):
        - <name>x_casemgmt_validate_resolved_transition</name> uses
          the x_casemgmt scope prefix per the auto-assigned scoped-
          app namespace.
        - <sys_scope>x_casemgmt</sys_scope> binds THIS subflow record
          to the x_casemgmt scope.
        - <sys_package source="x_casemgmt">x_casemgmt</sys_package>
          binds THIS subflow record to the x_casemgmt application
          package.
        - The Flow Designer snapshot below references:
            * x_casemgmt_case table BY NAME
              (input parameter reference_table)
            * x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator Script Include BY
              API NAME (the canonical scope-qualified accessor for
              scoped Script Includes; see
              ../../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml
              <api_name>x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator</api_name>)
            * x_casemgmt_case_task table indirectly (via the Script
              Include's getOpenTaskCountForCase which constructs
              new GlideAggregate('x_casemgmt_case_task'))
        Zero global-scope writes. Zero modifications to OOB tables
        (sys_user, sys_user_group, sys_user_role, core_company,
         task, incident, etc.).

    NO-HARDCODED-SYS_ID CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):
        - <sys_scope> resolves the scope record BY NAME (x_casemgmt)
        - <sys_package> resolves the application record BY NAME
          (x_casemgmt) via its `source` attribute
        - The subflow snapshot references the x_casemgmt_case table
          BY NAME ("reference_table": "x_casemgmt_case") and invokes
          the Script Include BY API NAME
          ("x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator"). Zero `sys_id`
          literal references appear anywhere in the snapshot or
          audit-field XML.
        - The <sys_id> element below is THIS record's own deterministic
          primary key (MD5 of "x_casemgmt_validate_resolved_transition"),
          which is permitted because the AAP "no hardcoded sys_id" rule
          applies to REFERENCE FIELDS pointing at OTHER records, not to
          a record's own primary key. The deterministic derivation
          ensures idempotent re-import on a fresh PDI - re-importing
          the same Update Set produces the same sys_id, which collides
          on the existing record and updates it in place rather than
          creating a duplicate.
        - The Script Include's getOpenTaskCountForCase uses
          caseGr.getUniqueValue() to obtain the case sys_id at runtime
          - this is a runtime value, not a hardcoded literal.

    EMAIL-DISABLED CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):
        The subflow MUST NOT call gs.eventQueue('...') for any email
        notification event since email is disabled on the PDI. This
        subflow contains zero gs.eventQueue() calls, zero Send Email
        actions, and zero notification trigger steps. It performs
        only the validation-and-throw side effect on failure.
        Intentionally diverges from ArkCase ChangeCaseFileStateService
        line 106 raiseEvent() which would have triggered downstream
        notification listeners on every state change; the ServiceNow
        POC omits the equivalent call per the AAP minimal-change
        clause and the email-disabled constraint.

    NO PII (AAP Section 0.7.2):
        The description text, code comments, and snapshot inline
        labels contain zero real names, real email addresses, real
        phone numbers, real organizational identifiers, or any
        other personally identifiable information. The subflow
        operates exclusively on a case-row reference and emits a
        generic, AAP-mandated error string.

    ACTIVE-PUBLISHED STATE (CRITICAL per agent prompt Phase 2.3):
        - <active>true</active>      - subflow is enabled, NOT Draft
        - <status>published</status> - subflow is published, NOT draft
        Both are required for the parent flows to be able to call
        this subflow at runtime. A Draft-state subflow is callable
        only from the Flow Designer canvas during testing; published
        is the production-ready state.

    TYPE=SUBFLOW (CRITICAL per agent prompt Phase 2.4):
        - <type>subflow</type>
        Subflows are reusable building blocks called by parent flows
        via the "Call a Subflow" action. A type=flow record cannot
        be called by another flow; the platform looks for type=subflow
        records when resolving a "Call a Subflow" reference. The
        parent flows in ../general_inquiry_state_machine.xml and
        ../complaint_state_machine.xml reference this subflow BY
        NAME (x_casemgmt_validate_resolved_transition), and the
        platform's lookup at activation time resolves to THIS record
        because of the type=subflow setting.

    RUN_AS=CALLER (CRITICAL per agent prompt Phase 2.4):
        - <run_as>caller</run_as>
        The subflow inherits the run-as context of the calling parent
        flow. The parent flows use run_as=user_who_triggers, so when
        the parent calls this subflow, the subflow ALSO runs as the
        triggering user. This ensures:
            * The Script Include's gs.getUser().hasRole() calls (if
              any future enhancement adds them) evaluate against the
              correct user identity.
            * Any future audit logging tracks the actual user who
              attempted the Resolved transition, not the system
              account.
            * The GlideAggregate query in getOpenTaskCountForCase
              respects the caller's read ACLs on x_casemgmt_case_task.
              In the ACL matrix from AAP Section 0.5.6, all three
              roles (case_manager, case_agent, case_viewer) have
              read access on case_task rows whose parent case is
              within their visibility - so this is generally a
              no-op constraint, but the run_as=caller setting
              guarantees correctness if ACLs are tightened later.

    UPDATE-SET LOAD ORDER (AAP Section 0.5.2):

        This sys_hub_flow record MUST be loaded AFTER:

          - ../../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml
              (scoped application; <sys_package> reference resolution)
          - ../../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml
              (scope record; <sys_scope> reference resolution)
          - ../../tables/x_casemgmt_case.xml
              (parent table; the case_record input parameter is a
               Reference to this table)
          - ../../tables/x_casemgmt_case_task.xml
              (child table queried by the Script Include's
               getOpenTaskCountForCase via GlideAggregate)
          - ../../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_status.xml
              (the field whose change to 'Resolved' triggers the
               parent flow's OnUpdate filter; must exist before the
               parent flow's trigger filter can resolve)
          - ../../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_task_case.xml
              (the reference field used by the GlideAggregate
               addQuery('case', caseSysId) filter; must exist
               before the Script Include's query can resolve)
          - ../../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_task_status.xml
              (the field used in the addQuery('status', '!=', 'Closed')
               filter; must exist with the 'Closed' choice value)
          - ../../choices/sys_choice_case_task_status.xml
              (the choice list that defines the 'Closed' literal;
               the GlideAggregate filter literal 'Closed' must
               match this choice value's `value` attribute)
          - ../../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml
              (the Script Include this subflow invokes; must exist
               and be activated before the subflow's Script Step can
               resolve the API name x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator)

        And BEFORE:

          - ../general_inquiry_state_machine.xml
              (parent flow that calls this subflow on the General
               Inquiry case-type's In Progress -> Resolved edge)
          - ../complaint_state_machine.xml
              (parent flow that calls this subflow on the Complaint
               case-type's In Progress -> Resolved edge)

    DETERMINISTIC SYS_ID:
        sys_id = MD5("x_casemgmt_validate_resolved_transition")
               = c8fde9d4675c53e1c14e40c0503835f0
        32-character lowercase hex. The PDI accepts any valid 32-char
        hex sys_id; deriving from the record name guarantees idempotent
        re-import on a fresh PDI: re-importing the same Update Set
        produces the same sys_id, which collides on the existing
        record and updates it in place rather than creating a
        duplicate. This is the same convention used by every other
        deterministically-keyed record in this Update Set (e.g., the
        peer subflow validate_pending_transition.xml whose sys_id is
        94063d7d535c4e841ad7deb0b45e8ba5 = MD5 of
        "x_casemgmt_validate_pending_transition").

    VALIDATION GATE MAPPING (AAP Section 0.7.3):

        - Gate 2 (Workflow): "All state transitions enforced for both
          case types - Invalid transitions return blocking error;
          task-closure check blocks Resolved transition." THIS subflow
          is the CORE IMPLEMENTATION of the "task-closure check
          blocks Resolved transition" requirement. The gate is
          verified by:

              1) Create a case in 'In Progress' status with
                 assigned_agent populated (and assigned_group set
                 to a group of which the agent is a member).
              2) Create a child x_casemgmt_case_task linked to the
                 case via the `case` reference field, with
                 status = 'Open' (or 'In Progress'; anything not
                 'Closed').
              3) Attempt to set the case's status to 'Resolved'
                 (e.g., via the form's Save button).
              4) The parent flow (general_inquiry or complaint
                 state_machine, depending on case.type) fires on
                 the OnUpdate trigger filtered to status -> Resolved.
              5) The parent flow calls this subflow with
                 case_record = $trigger.current.
              6) This subflow's Script Step runs the validator,
                 which detects openCount > 0 via GlideAggregate.
              7) The validator returns
                 { ok: false, error: 'All tasks must be closed
                                       before resolving this case.' }
              8) This subflow's If condition (ok == false) is true.
              9) The Throw Error action fires with the verbatim
                 message.
             10) The parent flow's transaction aborts; the form
                 displays the verbatim error.
             11) The case row remains at status='In Progress' (the
                 update was rolled back; the new value 'Resolved'
                 was never persisted).

          The character-for-character verbatim message check is
          NON-NEGOTIABLE. Any deviation FAILS Gate 2. Examples of
          INCORRECT messages that would FAIL the gate:
              - "All Tasks Must Be Closed Before Resolving This Case."
                (Title Case)
              - "All tasks must be closed before resolving this case"
                (missing trailing period)
              - "All tasks must be closed before resolving the case."
                (the -> this)
              - "All tasks must be closed before resolving this Case."
                (Case capitalized)
              - "All tasks must be closed before resolving the case"
                (missing period AND wrong article)
          The CORRECT message that passes Gate 2 is exactly:
              All tasks must be closed before resolving this case.
          (lowercase 'case', trailing period, ASCII straight quotes
          when quoted, no leading/trailing whitespace.)

        - Gate 7 (Update Set): "Scoped app exported - Update Set
          loads without errors on a fresh PDI instance." The
          deterministic sys_id, reference-by-name pattern, and well-
          formed XML structure ensure this record re-imports cleanly
          with zero preview errors. The CDATA-wrapped JSON snapshot
          contains characters requiring CDATA escaping (curly braces,
          quotes within JSON, the != comparison operator), and the
          CDATA section is properly opened and closed around both
          <latest_snapshot> and <master_snapshot> elements.

    PERFORMANCE NOTE:
        getOpenTaskCountForCase uses GlideAggregate which executes
        SQL COUNT(*) rather than fetching all task rows. For cases
        with many child tasks (a hundred or more), this is far more
        efficient than the equivalent
            new GlideRecord('x_casemgmt_case_task').addQuery(...)
            .query(); var count = gr.getRowCount();
        pattern. The validator returns as soon as the aggregate
        cursor advances by one row, so even thousands of open tasks
        on a single case incur near-constant evaluation cost on the
        gate path.

    DEFENSE-IN-DEPTH NOTE:
        A before-update Business Rule could ALSO enforce the all-
        tasks-closed gate (and the AAP allows this pattern), but
        the subflow is the primary surface in the current AAP
        scope. If a future enhancement adds a Business Rule
        equivalent (for catching direct DB updates that bypass the
        flow path - e.g., Table API updates from external
        integrations), it would live at
        ../../business_rules/x_casemgmt_block_resolved_with_open_tasks.xml
        and would call the same Script Include method
        canTransitionToResolved for code reuse. Adding the Business
        Rule is NOT currently in the AAP scope.

    FUTURE EXTENSIBILITY:
        - If a future AAP enhancement adds a 'Reopened' status that
          allows transitions from Closed back to In Progress, this
          subflow would still apply to subsequent Resolved
          transitions and would still enforce the all-tasks-closed
          gate. The gate is on the DESTINATION status (Resolved),
          not the source, so it transparently handles re-entry.
        - If task statuses expand beyond Open/In Progress/Closed
          (e.g., adding 'Cancelled' or 'On Hold'), the
          addQuery('status', '!=', 'Closed') filter still treats
          all non-Closed values as "open" for gate purposes, which
          is the AAP-aligned behavior (a non-Closed task should
          not be deemed sufficient to allow Resolved). Cancelled
          tasks would need to be explicitly Closed before the case
          can be Resolved, OR the Choice list could replace the
          'Cancelled' value with a final-state 'Closed' equivalent.
        - If email is later re-enabled on the PDI and a
          "Case has been Resolved - all tasks closed" notification
          is desired, add a Send Email step to the parent flows
          (after the subflow returns successfully), NOT to this
          subflow. This subflow's responsibility is gating only;
          notification is a separate concern.
-->
